Since my last post, my role has started to become more focused on the actual back-end relationship between the student and admin parts of the website. Earlier in the project, I was mostly helping think through the schema and how the big pieces should connect. Now, I've started thinking more about how those ideas actually work on the website when someone is clicking through it.

Preparing for the second client meeting also helped me understand what parts of the website needed to be clearer. It's one thing to talk about a schema or a mockup, but it's different when the client needs to see pages that can actually be clicked through. I helped think through what the admin and student sides should show, and how the project information should be displayed so that it makes sense to both types of users.

I've also started to think about permissions. The student side and admin side should not show the same things. Students should not see the approval or denial tools, but they should see the result and any feedback that was sent to them. Admins need to be able to search for students, view their projects, see their logged hours, and understand what organizations students are working with. Making that separation clear is one of the main things I want to keep working on, right now our website isn't making that disctincion clear.

Moving forward, I want to keep improving the back-end and admin features. I'm going to make the student search page work well, clean up the way volunteer hours are displayed, and eventually help with the mentor assignment system. I still need the list of mentors and their attributes from the client, but for now implementing it and making sure it works is my focus. 